'''HMS ''Albacore''''' was a "thirty-knotter" [[destroyer]] of the British [[Royal Navy]], which was later classified as part of the [[B-class destroyer (1913)|B class]]. She was built by Palmer's of Yarrow as a private venture, launching in 1906, and being purchased in 1909. She served through the [[First World War]] before being sold for scrap in 1919.
==Construction and design== The shipbuilder [[Palmers Shipbuilding and Iron Company]] laid down two destroyers on speculation (i.e. without a specific order) on 1 September 1905, as Yard Number 786 and 787.<ref name="Lyon p37">Lyon 2001, p. 37.</ref>{{#tag:ref|It is unknown whether Palmer's had any specific customer in mind for these two ships.<ref name="Friedman p63"/>|group=lower-alpha}} The two destroyers were of generally similar size and design to the Royal Navy's earlier "thirty knotter" destroyers (later redesignated as the [[B-class destroyer (1913)|B]], [[C-class destroyer (1913)|C]] or [[D-class destroyer (1913)|D class]] depending on the number of funnels), with a turtleback [[forecastle]],<ref name="Conways p73">Gardiner and Gray 1985, p. 73.</ref> with the Royal Navy having abandoned the "thirty-knotter" type for the [[River-class destroyer]]s, with a higher raised forecastle instead of a turtleback, and sacrificing high speed in [[sea trial]]s in favour of greater seaworthiness.<ref name="manning p47">Manning 1961, p. 47.</ref> The first of the two ships, which would later become HMS ''Albacore'', was launched on 9 October 1906.<ref name="Lyon p37"/> Palmer's was unable to find a customer for these ships, however,<ref name="Lyon p25">Lyon 2001, p. 25.</ref> and offered to sell them to the Royal Navy on 5 December 1907 for [[Pound sterling|£]]70,000–80,000 each. The [[Admiralty]] rejected the offer in February 1908, but in April two destroyers, {{HMS|Tiger|1900|2}} and {{HMS|Gala|1905|2}}, were lost in accidents and it was decided to order the two stock ships from Palmer's as replacements. A provisional order for the two ships was placed on 8 May 1908, at a price of £60,000 each, depending on successful trials, with a speed of {{convert|31|kn|lk=in}} being required.<ref name="Lyon p37-8">Lyon 2001, pp. 37–38.</ref>
[[File:HMS Bonetta (1871) IWM SP 003104.jpg|thumb|left|''Albacore''{{'}}s sister ship {{HMS|Bonetta|1907|6}}]] Unlike most "thirty-knotter"s, the new ships were powered by [[steam turbine]]s rather than [[Marine_steam_engine#Triple_or_multiple_expansion|triple expansion engines]], with four Reed boilers feeding steam at {{convert|250|psi}} to [[Parsons Marine Steam Turbine Company|Parsons]] direct drive turbines which drove two shafts, generating {{convert|6000|shp|lk=in}}.<ref name="Friedman p63">Friedman 2009, p. 63.</ref><ref name="manning p46">Manning 1961, p. 46.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Sources differ as to the fuel used to power the ships, with some stating that they were oil-fuelled,<ref name="manning p46"/><ref name="Conways p73"/> while others say that they used coal. <ref name="Lyon p37"/><ref name="Friedman p63,292">Friedman 2009, pp. 63, 292.</ref>|group=lower-alpha}} The ships had four funnels, with the middle two funnels closely spaced.<ref name="Friedman p63"/>
''Albacore''{{'}}s hull was {{convert|220|ft|10|in|m}} long [[overall length|overall]] and {{convert|215|ft|3|m}} [[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]], with a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|21|ft|0+1/4|in|m|2}} and a [[Draft (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|6|ft|5+1/2|in|m|2}}. She [[Displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{convert|408|LT}} normal load and {{convert|440|LT}} deep load.<ref name="Friedman p292">Friedman 2009, p. 292.</ref> The ship's [[Stem (ship)|stem]] was higher than earlier turtleback destroyers, while rather than the narrow [[conning tower]] of the earlier destroyers, ''Albacore'' had a full width [[Bridge (nautical)|bridge]] situated further aft, which was claimed by Palmer's to make the ship much dryer in heavy seas.<ref name="Lyon p37"/><ref name="Friedman p63"/> Gun armament consisted of three [[QF 12 pounder 12 cwt naval gun]]s, with two situated side by side on top of the bridge and one aft.<ref name="Friedman p63"/> Two 18 inch (450 mm) torpedo tubes were carried,<ref name="Conways p73"/> while the ship had a complement of 56 officers and men.<ref name="Friedman p292"/>
==Service== Although it was hoped that the ship could be accepted quickly, with delivery expected within two to three months of the order being placed, official [[sea trials]] proved problematical. ''Albacore'' only reached a maximum of {{convert|26.75|kn}} instead of the required 31 knots,<ref name="Lyon p38-9">Lyon 2001, pp. 38–39.</ref> which may have been due to more realistic trial conditions.<ref name="Friedman p63"/> The Admiralty finally agreed to accept ''Albacore'' and her sister ship ''Bonetta'' on 3 March 1909, paying £45,000 for each.<ref name="Lyon p39">Lyon 2001, p. 39.</ref> HMS ''Albacore'' was commissioned on 27 March that year.<ref name="Friedman p304">Friedman 2009, p. 304.</ref>
''Albacore'' was part of the Fourth Destroyer Flotilla in 1910, and of the Sixth Flotilla in 1913.<ref name="nmm">{{cite web|url=http://www.rmg.co.uk/sites/default/files/media/pdf//Warship_Histories_Vessels_v.pdf|title=NMM, vessel ID 379604|work=Warship Histories, vol v|publisher=[[National Maritime Museum]]|accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref> On 30 August 1912 the Admiralty directed all destroyers were to be grouped into classes designated by letters based on appearance.<ref name="Conways p18">Gardiner and Gray 1985, p. 18.</ref><ref name="Manning p17-8">Manning 1961, pp. 17–18.</ref> As a four-funneled ship, ''Albacore'' was listed as a [[B-class destroyer (1913)|B-class destroyer]] on 1 October 1913.<ref name="Conways p73"/>
On the outbreak of the [[First World War]] in August 1914, ''Albacore'' was sent to [[Scapa Flow]] to join the local patrol flotilla protecting the anchorage of the [[Grand Fleet]].<ref name="Conways p73"/><ref name="Ditt p58">Dittmar and Colledge 1972, p. 58.</ref> ''Albacore'' was heavily damaged on 9 March 1917 when she struck a mine laid by the German submarine {{SMU|UC-44||2}} off [[Kirkwall]], her bow being blown off and 17 of her crew being killed,<ref name=uboat>{{cite web|last=Helgason|first=Guðmundur|title=HMS Albacore|url=http://www.uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/147.html|work=Ships hit during WWI|publisher=uboat.net|accessdate=5 April 2014}}</ref><ref name="navhist cas317">{{cite web|last=Kindell|first=Don|title=1st - 31st MARCH 1917: in date, ship/unit & name order|url=http://www.naval-history.net/xDKCas1917-03Mar.htm|work=World War 1 - Casualty Lists of the Royal Navy and Dominion Navies|publisher=naval-history.net|accessdate=5 April 2014}}</ref> but was later repaired,<ref name="Conways p73"/> being back in service by July 1917.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Supplement to the Monthly Naval List Showing Organisation of the Fleet, Flag Officers' Commands &c.|date=July 1917|page=12|url=http://digital.nls.uk/british-military-lists/pageturner.cfm?id=94241378|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>
==Fate== ''Albacore'' was sold for scrap on 1 August 1919.<ref name="Ditt p58"/> ==Pennant numbers== {| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center" !Pennant number<ref name="Ditt p58" /> ||Date |- |P14||1914 |- |D76||August 1915 |- |D01||January 1918 |} ==Notes== {{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}
